entry.title: [Autofill] Check if focused frame is a descendant of delegate_'s frame
entry.content:
AutofillPopupControllerImpl works with a AutofillPopupDelegate, which is

associated with a RenderFrameHost, and a focused RenderFrameHost.

These two RenderFrameHosts are not necessarily identical.



This CL checks that the first RFH is an ancestor of the second RFH.

We support this case because it is common with frame-transcending forms

and can also happen due to race conditions.



This will become necessary once the CL crrev.com/c/5314761 removes

the deletion callback from AutofillPopupDelegate, which hides the

Autofill popup.



The new approach is certainly not great either, but it has two

advantages over the deletion callback:

- One less call to the very complex hiding mechanism of

AutofillPopupControllerImpl.

- Better for tests: the deletion callback leads to strange WeakPtr

invalidation and to virtual calls from destructors.

entry.title: Modernize some browsing_data enums
entry.content:
No behavior change.

* Remove BrowsingDataType::BOOKMARKS, it was unused.

* For BrowsingDataType and ClearBrowsingDataTab, instead of having a

NUM_ENTRIES sentinel (last value + 1), use a MAX_VALUE one (last value).

This spares some NOTREACHED() in switch statements.

entry.title: Autofill-based saved state notification implementation
entry.content:
The saved state notification is a popup that fades away after a few

seconds (controlled by a finch param, with default of 2 seconds).

The notification is shown immediately after the compose dialog loses

focus, but not when the close button is clicked and the session closed.



To the user, the saved state notification is perceived as the same UI

as the compose nudge when there is a saved session.



Previously, we tried to implement the saved state notification in WebUI,

but it's styling and positioning did not exactly match the autofill UI

and therefore it looked jarring to the user. This implementation

directly invokes autofill to show the autofill UI with a saved state

suggestion. It also adds a timer to fade away the autofill popup if the

PopupItemId is the saved state notification.

entry.title: Use dynamic cursor size on Intel GPUs
entry.content:
There's a separate cursor plane on Intel GPUs, which supports various

buffer sizes with some fixed widths. According to Intel GPU spec and

i915 driver code, Intel GPUs support cursor buffer with width of 64,

128 or 256 for the cursor plane [1].



Currently Chromium uses the default max buffer size supported

(256x256), while most of the cursor bitmap are smaller than 64x64 (e.g.

32x32 for the default cursor style).



Experiments show that using smaller cursor size can reduce power

consumption. On an ADL chromebook, using 64x64 cursor instead of the

default shows ~13% package power gain for video playback and ~0.8% for

video conferencing (Meet 1:1).



This CL introduces a mechanism that can dynamically change the buffer

size for cursor plane based on the input cursor bitmap.



[1] https://github.com/torvalds/linux/blob/v6.8-rc1/drivers/gpu/drm/i915/display/intel_cursor.c#L367

entry.title: Shared Storage: Save expected histogram sample counts from perf tests
entry.content:
We calculate and save the expected sample counts for the shared

storage specific histograms for the current benchmark run in a file

in the data directory (ignored by the newly added .gitignore). This

will enable the post-processing script (to be added in a followup) to

check whether the actual sample counts are equal to the expected

counts.

the data directory for the post-processing script to read. This script

will be added in https://crrev.com/c/5321541.
